  "prompt": "Did we get a better class of presidential nominee when the party bosses selected the candidate? Weren't the bosses more pragmatic than ideological?",
  "response": "The idea that party bosses were more pragmatic than ideological and selected better presidential nominees is a debated topic. Historically, the process of selecting candidates by party bosses or at conventions involved decision-makers who were often deeply entrenched in the political system and might have had significant practical experience. These individuals were usually concerned with the electability of candidates and maintaining party unity, which could influence their choices to favor more pragmatic candidates.\n\nBefore the modern primary system took hold (roughly in the early 20th century), candidates were often chosen by a relatively small group of party insiders. Many argue that the bosses had a vested interest in choosing candidates who could win and govern effectively, which might sometimes mean picking individuals with a broad appeal or those who could navigate the complex political terrain of the time. This could indeed result in more pragmatic choices.\n\nHowever, the system also had significant drawbacks. It was less democratic and less transparent, often favoring the interests of a select few over the broader preferences of the electorate. This could lead to the selection of candidates who were more aligned with party insiders' interests and not necessarily those who represented the will of the general population.\n\nThe shift to the modern primary system was intended to democratize the nomination process, allowing regular voters to have a direct say in which candidates would represent their party in the general election. While this has increased ideological diversity and given voice to various factions within each party, it has also sometimes resulted in more polarized candidates, as they must appeal to the more ideologically driven segments of their party base to win primaries.\n\nIn conclusion, whether the party bosses selected better nominees is a nuanced question. They might have been more pragmatic in certain ways, but the modern primary system, despite its issues, provides a broader and more democratic involvement in the selection process, reflecting a wider range of voters' preferences.",
